Topic modeling - LDA and STM

Guided practice

In this guided practice we will learn how to train a LDA model in R using the State of the Union discourses.

Loading libraries and data

library(tidyverse)
library(tidytext)
library(topicmodels)
library(textclean)
  
data <- read_csv('data/state_ofthe_union_texts.csv')

data <- data %>% janitor::clean_names() # column names normalization

data <- data %>%
  filter(year >= 1934) # filter discourses from 1934

data <- data %>% 
  mutate(id = row_number()) %>%
  select(id, everything())

data <- data %>% mutate(text = str_replace_all(text, "[:digit:]", ""))
#data <- data %>% mutate(text = str_replace_all(text, ". . . . .", ""))
data <- data %>% mutate(text = str_replace_all(text, "", "'"))
data <- data %>% mutate(text = replace_contraction(text))
#data <- data %>% mutate(text = str_replace_all(text, "[:punct:]", ""))
data <- data %>% mutate(text = str_replace_all(text, "[\\[\\]]", ""))
data <- data %>% mutate(text = str_replace_all(text, "'", ""))
data <- data %>% mutate(text = str_replace_all(text, "\"", ""))

Preprocessing

We will train LDA using unigrams:

token_unigrams <- data %>%
  select(id, president, year, text) %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, text)

token_unigrams %>%
  group_by(id) %>%
  summarise(n=n())

Notice that unnest_tokens took care of several preprocessing stages:

  • Other columns, such as the line number each word came from, are retained.
  • Punctuation has been stripped.
  • By default, unnest_tokens() converts the tokens to lowercase, which makes them easier to compare or combine with other datasets. (Yo can use the to_lower = FALSE argument to turn off this behavior).

We can now eliminate stopwords (we added some custom stopwords):

stop_words_data <- stop_words
stop_words_data <- stop_words_data %>% 
  add_row(word = c('united', 'states', 'u. s.', 'u.s', 
                   'program', 'programs',
                   'government', 'congress', 
                   'applause', 'tonight', 'nation', 'nations', 'national',
                   'administration',
                   'country', 'americans',
                   'public', 'people', 'america', 'american', 'world'))

token_unigrams <- token_unigrams %>%
  anti_join(stop_words_data)

We generate the word count table.

word_count <- token_unigrams %>%
  group_by(id, president, year, word) %>%
  summarise(n = n()) %>%
  ungroup()

word_count

Formatting TFM

Our data frame word_counts is in a tidy form, with one-term-per-document-per-row. We need to transform it to a DocumentTermMatrix, the format required by topicmodels package. We can cast a one-token-per-row table into a DocumentTermMatrix with tidytexts cast_dtm().

dtm <- word_count %>% cast_dtm(id, word, n)

Train LDA

We can use the LDA() function from the topicmodels package, setting \(k = 4\), to create a fairly simple four-topic LDA model.

tictoc::tic()
lda <- LDA(dtm, k = 4, control = list(seed = 753))
tictoc::toc()
## 10.567 sec elapsed

This was the easy part. The main problem will be will involve exploring and interpreting the model using tidying functions from the tidytext package.

Word-topic probabilities

The tidytext package offers a method to extract per-topic-per-word probabilities from the model, referred to as \(\beta\) (beta).

word2topics <- tidy(lda, matrix = "beta")
word2topics

The output of applying tidy() to LDA object is a table in one-topic-per-term-per-row format. For each combination, the model computes the probability of that term being generated from that topic. For example, the term abolished has an almost zero probability of being generated from topics 4 or 5, but it increases to 0.000030 to belong to topic 1.

Lets find the most frequent terms for each topic and make a nice plot:

top_terms <- word2topics %>%
  group_by(topic) %>%
  slice_max(beta, n = 10) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  arrange(topic, -beta)

top_terms %>%
  mutate(term = reorder_within(term, beta, topic)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(beta, term, fill = factor(topic))) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ topic, scales = "free") +
  scale_y_reordered() +
  theme_minimal()

This visualization allows us to comprehend the two topics extracted from the articles. In topic 1, the most prevalent words include war, federal, economic and peace meaning that armed conflicts and some issues related to fiscal expenditure could be relevant. Topic 2 is characterized by very similar words (paece, free, federal, economic). Topic 3 mentions wars like children, time, health, security, which could be pointing to issues related to social security and health care. Finally, topic 4 uses words like jobs, time, economy, so it is possible to infer that this theme is related to labor economy and job situation.

Some words means seems to have similar or related meaning are present in both topics: war, future, time. This shows an advantage of topic modeling over hard clustering methods: topics in natural language often exhibit some overlap in terms of words.

Topics 1 and 2 seems to be overlapping. So, it is possible that we will need to train a model with more topics (higher \(k\)). You will try this in independent practice.

Document-topic probabilities

LDA also allows us to model documents as a mixture of topics. We can analyze the document-topic probabilities matrix using tidy() and setting matrix="gamma".

doc2topics <- tidy(lda, matrix="gamma")
doc2topics %>%
  mutate(document=as.numeric(document)) %>%
  arrange(document, topic, desc(gamma))

The model estimates that document 1 has roughly the same proportion of words of topic 1 and topic 2. Many of these documents share this characteristic: they were drawn from a mix of the two topics. These is another indicator that we should use a higher \(k\).

Visualizing and interpreting topics

Until now, we have used the probabilities of each word belonging to each topic as a way to interpret what each topic is about. However, as mentioned above, there are several words that repeat across more than one topic (war, peace, federal) and, moreover, they appear with high probabilities of belonging to each one. Other words seem to belong more exclusively to a certain topic.

It would be useful, then, to be able to differentiate words according to some metric that gives us an idea of the importance of each word in each topic and that does not take into account or discount the relevance of each word over the total corpus. That is the function of the relevance metric \(r\) (Sievert and Shirley 2014).

\[r(w,k|\lambda) = \lambda log(\phi_{kw}) + (1-\lambda) log(\frac{\phi_{kw}}{p_{w}})\] The relevance of a word \(w\) within a topic \(k\) (\(r(kw|\lambda)\)) is a function of the logarithms of the probability of \(w\) belonging to \(k\) (\(\phi_{kw}\)) and the lift, that is, the ratio between that probability and the marginal probability of each \(w\) in the total corpus (\(\frac{\phi_{kw}}{p_{w}}\)). In turn, there is an adjustment parameter \(\lambda\) that serves to control the weight of each component in the total metric. Thus, \(\lambda=0\) only ranks the words based on the lift. On the other hand, \(\lambda=1\) generates the metric we have worked with so far and allows ranking the words based on their probability of belonging to the topic.

Fortunately, there is a library that allows us to visualize all this information in a graphical and quite useful way.

LDAvis

Lets load LDAvis:

library(LDAvis)

The main problem is that LDAvis is a rather old library and it has been written using some old-fashioned packages like quanteda or tm. So, in order to use it in our example with Here we have written a small function to make the data migration from topicmodels.

topicmodels_json_ldavis <- function(fitted, word_count){
  # Find required quantities
  ## Generates word2topic matrix  
    phi <- tidy(lda, "beta") %>%
      pivot_wider(names_from = term,
                  values_from = beta) %>%
      column_to_rownames(var="topic") %>%
      as.matrix()
    
  ## Generates doc2topic matrix
    theta <- tidy(lda, "gamma") %>%
      pivot_wider(names_from = topic,
                  values_from = gamma) %>%
      column_to_rownames(var="document") %>%
      as.matrix()

  ## Generates vocabulary 
    vocab <- colnames(phi)
    
  ## Generates document length vector
    doc_length <- word_count %>% 
      group_by(id) %>% 
      summarise(n=sum(n)) %>%
      select(n) %>%
      pull()
    
  ## Generates marginal distribution of terms
    term_freq <- word_count %>%
      group_by(word) %>%
      summarise(n = sum(n)) 

  ## Function to correct a zeros error in LDAvis when K=2
     svd_tsne <- function(x) tsne::tsne(svd(x)$u)

  ## Convert to json
    json_lda <- LDAvis::createJSON(phi = phi, theta = theta,
                            vocab = vocab,
                            doc.length = doc_length,
                            term.frequency = term_freq$n,
                            mds.method = svd_tsne
                            )

    return(json_lda)
}

json_vis <- topicmodels_json_ldavis(lda, word_count)
serVis(json_vis, out.dir = "../17_topic_modeling/vis", open.browser = FALSE)

Unfortunately, we cannot embed the dashboard in the .rmd file, so we will only use a snapshot here. If you go to the Plots tab, you will be able to see the dashboard in interactive format.

The left panel provides information about two important questions:

  • How prevalent is each topic?
  • How do the topics relate to each other?

The relative position in a two-dimensional space of the mentioned \(k\) topics is projected. Different methods can be used for this purpose (PCA, t-SNE). Each topic is represented as a circle. In this case, t-SNE has been used. It can be observed that the circles are fairly separated from each other.

Furthermore, the area of the circles is proportional to the relevance of the topic in the overall corpus. Thus, in our case, topics 1, 2, and 3 represent 77.5% of the corpus.

As we click on each topic, the right panel changes. It provides significant assistance for interpreting the topics. It presents a list of words ordered for each topic. Additionally, there is a slider that controls the parameter \(\lambda\). Therefore, in the previous capture, \(\lambda=1\), so all terms of each topic are ordered based on their probability of belonging (similar to what we did in the previous plots). In this case, topic 4 had war, freedom, security, time, peace, and forces as its main words.

But if we modify the slider to \(\lambda=0.5\), this list changes:

Now the main words are war, Iraq, terrorist, fighting, and Iraqi. Now the topic takes on a much more specific sense, linked to the war on terrorism and specifically to Iraq.

You can try what happens with the other topics. Do their interpretations change when varying the metric to order the terms in each topic?

Structural Topic Modeling (STM)

The last technique we are going to review in this guided practice is STM. As we mentioned earlier, its main use is to allow the introduction of covariates in topic modeling and to enable topics (either their prevalence or content) to vary based on external variables or metadata.

To implement it, the stm library is required:

library(stm)

The usage is similar to the previous case. We just need to transform the tibble word_count into another object, a dfm:

dfm <- word_count %>%
                cast_dfm(id, word, n)

head(dfm)

Then, we can generate a tibble with the metadata we are going to use later:

metadata <- token_unigrams %>%
                  select(id, president, year) %>%
                  distinct() %>%
                  left_join(data %>% select(id, text))

And then, we call the stm function. We are going to use the year of the speech as a variable that affects the prevalence.

stm_4 <- stm(documents = dfm,
      K = 4,
      prevalence = ~year,
      max.em.its = 75, 
      data = metadata,
      init.type = "Spectral")

Some useful tools in STM

Now, once we have estimated our STM topic model, it is extremely important to proceed with its validation. Lets see that the stm package has implemented some functions that make this validation task quite easy.

Lets explore two possible ways to proceed with model validation. The first one is to analyze the words that are part of each topic. This is similar to what we have been doing so far, but with a difference: until now, we had been working with the words that have the highest , that is, the highest probability of belonging to each topic. STM allows us to obtain other lists of words. Lets call the following function:

labelTopics(stm_4)
## Topic 1 Top Words:
##       Highest Prob: time, children, care, health, budget, tax, jobs 
##       FREX: crime, parents, st, century, college, family, children 
##       Lift: aaron, abess, abm, absent, accessibility, acquisitions, ad 
##       Score: medicare, internet, brady, parents, students, bosnia, environment 
## Topic 2 Top Words:
##       Highest Prob: war, dollars, million, peace, time, production, expenditures 
##       FREX: estimated, liquidation, japanese, receipts, expenditures, navy, reconversion 
##       Lift: aaa, abdicated, ablaze, ably, abnormal, abovementioned, absentee 
##       Score: liquidation, reconversion, demobilization, expenditures, hitler, autocracy, vj 
## Topic 3 Top Words:
##       Highest Prob: federal, economic, peace, free, security, defense, military 
##       FREX: communists, soviet, communist, relations, aggression, atomic, assistance 
##       Lift: a.d, abating, abridges, abrupt, absorbs, absurd, accelerates 
##       Score: communists, communist, xa, recommend, disarmament, partnership, postal 
## Topic 4 Top Words:
##       Highest Prob: jobs, energy, security, economy, time, tax, health 
##       FREX: lets, weve, thats, cant, its, im, iraqis 
##       Lift: a.s, abbas, abortions, abstinence, abusing, accessing, accumulates 
##       Score: thats, its, terrorists, weve, im, lets, qaeda

This output shows four lists of words. Lets focus on the first two:

  • Highest prob: These are the words within each topic with the highest probability (directly inferred from the topic-word distribution parameter ). These are the ones we used in the plots above.

  • FREX: This is a metric that attempts to combine frequency () with exclusivity. In other words, words with high FREX are distinctive words for topics: they are both frequent and exclusive. This is calculated by taking the harmonic mean of the rank by probability within the topic (frequency, i.e., the parameter ), and exclusivity is a measure that tries to quantify the relative use of a term in a topic compared to its use in other topics.

Thus, the distribution of words according to FREX in topic 4 shows that some contractions survived without expansion (lets, weve, etc.). However, iraqis is a relevant term.

To examine documents that are highly associated with topics, the findThoughts() function can be used. This function will print out the documents highly associated with each topic. Reading these documents is useful for understanding the content of a topic and interpreting its definition.

To make them easier to read, lets limit them to a few characters of each document.

findThoughts(stm_4, 
             texts= metadata %>% mutate(text = str_sub(text, 200, 600)) %>% select(text) %>% pull(), 
             n=10, 
             topics=4)

Workflow scheme
